06.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, for example in Lincolnshire, Lancashire, Herefordshire, and North Yorkshire, all named with Old English <i>croft</i> ‘small arable enclosure (normally adjoining a house)’, or a topographic name for someone who lived by a croft, from Middle English <i>croft</i>.","English: possibly in some cases a variant of   Craft   2.","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . Compare   Kroft   and   Craft  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craft","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>craft</i> ‘skillful, clever, learned’.","English: habitational name from Croft in Leicestershire. See also   Croft  .","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . See also   Croft  ."]},{"name":"Crate","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): from Middle English <i>crate</i> ‘hurdle, basket’, or occasionally perhaps from <i>crete</i> ‘cradle’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such articles. Alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Croft   1."]},{"name":"Crofts","meanings":["English: variant of   Croft  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Groft","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Croft  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":31,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Croft was born about 1228, in Herefordshire, England, his father, Hugh de Croft III, was 27 and his mother, Christina Southworth, was 49. He had at least 1 son with Isabel Longberch. He died in 1274, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1228–1274":"umbes 1228–1274","1228–1274":"1228–1274","1230–1298":"1230–1298","1254–1297":"1254–1297","1202–1278":"1202–1278","1180–1244":"1180–1244","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1202":"1202","1278":"1278","1244":"1244","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","1297":"1297","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","England":"England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1228–1274":"noin 1228–1274","1228–1274":"1228–1274","1230–1298":"1230–1298","1254–1297":"1254–1297","1202–1278":"1202–1278","1180–1244":"1180–1244","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","about 1228":"noin 1228","1202":"1202","1278":"1278","1244":"1244","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","1297":"1297","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","England":"England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1228–1274":"environ 1228–1274","1228–1274":"1228–1274","1230–1298":"1230–1298","1254–12